name: 04- Model Training and Prediction
content:
Model Training and Detection

Model Used:

The application uses the Isolation Forest algorithm, an unsupervised anomaly detection method that does not require labeled data. It identifies anomalies (1) and normal data points (0) by randomly partitioning the feature space and isolating observations with unusual patterns. This approach works effectively for both numeric and encoded categorical features, making it well-suited for clinical trial datasets with mixed variable types.

Features Details:

Key features leveraged for anomaly detection include:

  • Patient demographics: Age, Sex
  • Baseline clinical measures: HouseâBrackmann Score, Pain Level
  • Treatment specifics: Treatment Group, Prednisolone, Acyclovir
  • Symptom indicators: Facial Asymmetry, Inability to Close Eye, Loss of Taste, Pain Behind Ear, Sudden Facial Weakness
  • Medical history: Recent Viral Infection, Preexisting Diabetes, Preexisting Hypertension
  • Treatment timing: Time between onset of symptoms and start of treatment

Feature Importance:

Although Isolation Forest is unsupervised, the contribution of each feature to anomaly scores can be assessed by evaluating the impact of feature partitions on the isolation process. This helps highlight which variables are most influential in detecting anomalies in patient data.

Model Metrics:

Key metrics to evaluate the performance of the anomaly detection model include:

  • Detection Metrics: Precision, Recall, F1-Score â especially on historical anomalies or simulated validation sets.
  • Anomaly Scores: Continuous scores assigned to each data point indicating its degree of deviation from normal patterns.
  • Interpretability: The algorithm flags both the type and severity of anomalies per subject, visit, and variable, aiding clinical review and decision-making.

Overview:

The Isolation Forest model allows the Clinical-Trial-Anomaly app to automatically detect unusual patterns in clinical trial datasets, flagging potential data quality issues or protocol deviations early, thereby improving monitoring efficiency and patient safety.
